ives are mutually constituted.   In How Lifeworlds Work, Jackson draws on years of ethnographic fieldwork in West Africa to highlight the dynamic quality of human relationships and reinvigorate the study of kinship and ritual. How, he asks, do we manage the perpetual process of accommodation between social norms and personal emotions, impulses, and desires? How are these two dimensions of lived reality joined, and how are the dual imperatives of individual expression and collective viability managed? Drawing on the pragmatist tradition, psychology, and phenomenology, Jackson offers an unforgettable, beautifully written account of how we make, unmake, and remake, our lifeworlds.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aEmotionsxAnthropological aspects. 0aEthnologyzSierra Leone. 0aExistential phenomenology. 0aIntersubjectivity. 0aKinship. 0aKuranko (African people) 0aKuranko (African people). 0aPhenomenological anthropology. 0aRites and ceremonies. 4aaffect. 4aemotionality. 4aintersubjectivity. 4akinship. 4aritualization. 4asociality. 70(DE-601)100603353X0(DE-588)1145362095aKoranko2gnd 70(DE-601)1042886120(DE-588)4078931-7aEthnologie2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226492018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226492018.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles